fields.description: Engage in the process of making art from conceptualization through final product.
Describe the fundamental theories and practices surrounding a specific art form.
Recognize and describe how the arts both reflect and reshape culture.
Identify and describe texts using discipline-specific research tools and practice.
Examine and analyze the language and form of texts and cultural artifacts including rhetorical and stylistic features and genres.
Interpret and evaluate texts using discipline-specific literacy.
Respond to texts by critically reading and integrating existing scholarship, and develop new interpretations of texts and cultural artifacts.
Recognize the diverse backgrounds represented in United States society and describe how these diverse contexts lead to differing perspectives on various topics.
Reflect on our own backgrounds in relation to those of others to identify commonalities and differences.
Recognize how awareness of these differences can enhance our understanding of the world around us.
Identify and clearly and constructively discuss various issues related to diversity, inequality, and associated topics.
Analyze ways in which individual interactions, social structures, and power dynamics have shaped and challenged the ideals of freedom and equality in a diverse society.
Demonstrate elementary communicative proficiency in a foreign language.
Compare the structures of a foreign and native language to gain new insights into the ways that languages work.
Identify distinctive features of culture(s) associated with the language being studied in comparison to oneâ€™s native culture(s).
Recognize and analyze the ways that culture and language are related in cultural perspectives, practices, and products.
Acquire and critically evaluate ideas and information from a range of intellectual traditions.
Identify, explain, and engage in personal reflection on the ways in which knowledge is informed by our influences and shapes our worldviews.
Contribute to the ongoing search for truth that forms the core of our academic mission.
Develop the ability to interpret and analyze diverse texts, and to recognize the ways in which they connect to each other and to individual experiences.
Develop effective written communication skills, including the ability to articulate complex ideas and to build and support arguments.
Develop effective dialogue skills, including the ability to articulate complex ideas, respond constructively to the ideas of others, and address difficult topics respectfully.
Consider individual questions or topics from multiple perspectives.
Explain some of the variety of ways in which we acquire and communicate knowledge.
Recognize the similarities and differences in language, skills, and approach taken by different disciplines to the same topic.
Observe the types of conversations that take place between experts from different fields and the benefits and challenges of communicating across disciplines.
Recognize the ways in which an interdisciplinary approach can strengthen our understanding of the world around us.
Identify patterns of assumptions, values and/or practices in one or more countries, regions, or cultural areas outside of the United States.
Interpret and evaluate these patterns and their implications for individuals and/or communities.
Recognize historical, cultural, artistic, economic, social, political, or other perspectives of these countries or cultural areas.
Consider how these perspectives shape responses to issues of local and/or international importance.
Demonstrate effective oral communication skills in a variety of contexts, including both discussions and formal presentations.
Speak with confidence in both spontaneous and rehearsed formats.
Express ideas with precision and clarity, but also style and creativity.
Identify and apply techniques for effective verbal expression, including understanding the audience and building engagement.
Reason with data, read graphs or maps, draw inferences from data, and recognize sources of error.
Recognize the context in which quantitative information is provided and apply appropriate quantitative tools.
Apply quantitative tools to make decisions and solve problems in everyday life.
Have accurate intuition about the meaning of numbers, including estimating and comparing scale.
Be comfortable with quantitative ideas and confident in their ability to apply quantitative methods.
Explore and explain the role of individual courses as part of a liberal arts education.
Explore and explain connections between different general education courses, individual majors, past experiences, and future goals.
Articulate and develop a sense of purpose and goals for meaningful life and work.
Identify the underlying structural components of religious worldviews, and articulate how these are expressed in various world religions.
Examine the role of religion in shaping individual and community identities worldwide, and how these identities have influenced historical and/or contemporary societies.
Evaluate critically the interaction between religious values and daily life, and how such interaction can potentially both promote and resolve conflict.
Explore the structures and components of the natural world and our connection to it.
Engage in the process of science and explain its use as a tool for acquiring knowledge about the world.
Recognize the approaches scientists take to ask.
Develop the scientific literacy needed to interpret, evaluate and communicate scientific information from a range of sources to a range of audiences.
Recognize and understand patterns of human behavior, individually or in groups.
Understand social, economic, and/or political structures and the ways in which they affect and are affected by individuals and/or societies.
Develop a basic understanding of how theory, method, data, and/or the evaluation of evidence work together, from the unique perspective of the discipline involved.
Explain the holistic nature of wellness and describe how different areas of wellness are interrelated.
Demonstrate and put into practice the knowledge and skills necessary to live healthier lives in college and beyond.
Articulate the relationship between wellness and oneâ€™s ability to meet personal, academic, and life goals.
Practice writing as a process of motivated inquiry and an exploration of external ideas and information.
Structure arguments effectively and provide evidence to support them.
Write with clarity and precision, structuring thoughts in a coherent manner.
Effectively revise the content, grammar, and style of written work.
Develop an awareness of and confidence in oneâ€™s voice as a writer and be able to express ideas in a manner that is both engaging and appropriate for the audience.
Write effectively in discipline-appropriate style and in response to discipline-specific forms of inquiry.
